      commentary: "The first verse of the first Upanishad most people ever read makes a claim and issues an instruction, and both run against every instinct of a possessive age. The claim: everything — jagatyāṁ jagat, literally \"the moving in the moving,\" a world of flux inside a world of flux — is already suffused with something you did not make and cannot own. The instruction: therefore enjoy it by letting it go.\n\nNotice what the verse does not say. It does not say renounce the world and go to a cave. It says bhuñjīthāḥ — enjoy, savor, partake. The Upanishad's opening move is not to forbid enjoyment but to reveal its actual mechanism: tena tyaktena, \"through that letting-go.\" Grasping is not how we enjoy things; it is precisely how we stop enjoying them. The vacation photographed instead of lived, the possession that becomes a worry the moment it becomes ours, the relationship gripped so tightly it suffocates — everyone has run this experiment and gotten the same result. The verse states the finding 3,000 years early: possession and enjoyment are not the same operation, and they interfere with each other.\n\nThe closing question is the sharpest edge: kasya svid dhanam — whose is wealth, anyway? Hold anything you call \"mine\" and follow its history. The money was someone else's before you and will be someone else's after. The body assembled itself out of borrowed food. Even your talents were seeded by genes and teachers you did not choose. \"Ownership\" turns out to be a short-term rental agreement written in disappearing ink. The verse does not scold you for having things; it asks you to see through the fiction of \"having\" — and promises, strangely, that on the far side of that seeing lies more enjoyment, not less. This is the seed of everything the Gita will later call nishkama karma. Beyond outcomes begins here."
