      commentary: "If verse one could be mistaken for a call to withdraw from the world, verse two slams that door immediately: keep acting — and want to live long. Jijīviṣet śataṁ samāḥ: desire a hundred years of life. This is scripture telling you to want a full lifespan of engagement, work, and doing. Whatever the Upanishads are selling, it is not escape.\n\nThe hinge word is lipyate — to smear, to stick, to stain. Action itself was never the problem; the problem is action that adheres, work that hardens into identity and anxiety. Everyone knows both modes from the inside. There is work done as pure activity — absorbed, complete, finished when it is finished — and there is work done as self-construction, where every task carries a second invisible task: proving something, securing something, fearing something. The first kind washes off. The second kind clings, and we carry it into dinner, into sleep, into years of accumulated residue we eventually call burnout or bitterness.\n\nRead verses one and two as a single instruction, because they are one: see that nothing is finally yours (verse 1), and then act wholeheartedly for a hundred years (verse 2) — and acting from that seeing, na karma lipyate, the action leaves no stain. This is the exact teaching Krishna will hand Arjuna on the battlefield centuries later: your entitlement is to the action, never to its fruits. In an age when careers, outputs, and even identities are being automated out from under us, a way of working that does not depend on clinging to outcomes is no longer a spiritual luxury. It may be the only durable way to work at all."
