      commentary: "After two verses of luminous instruction, a warning — and its key word repays a careful look. Ātma-hanaḥ: the self-slayers. The commentators are clear this is not about physical suicide. The Self, the Upanishads will insist for verse after verse, cannot be killed. What can be done is stranger: it can be ignored to death. A life spent entirely on the surface — acquiring, comparing, scrolling, performing — is, in this verse's unsparing diagnosis, a slow killing of one's own depth. Not murder; neglect unto death.\n\nAndhena tamasā — blind darkness. The image is precise. Ordinary darkness is the absence of light; blind darkness is the absence of the very capacity to see, the state of no longer knowing that there is anything to look for. The deepest cost of an entirely outward life is not missing the answer but forgetting the question. And one need not die to visit these sunless worlds. Anyone who has surfaced from years of pure busyness and wondered, in a hotel room or a hospital corridor, \"who exactly has been living my life?\" has stood at their border.\n\nWhy place this warning third, before the teaching proper has even begun? Because the Upanishad is honest about stakes. Verses one and two offered the deal — see clearly, act freely. Verse three states the cost of refusing it: not punishment from outside, but the natural consequence of self-abandonment, the way darkness is the natural consequence of closing your eyes. The rest of the text is the way out — and it begins, in the very next verse, with a description of the One that outruns the mind."
